# Least Privilege

> [!word] Least Privilege
> Least Privilege is when a user or process is given access only to the resources necessary to complete a specific purpose.

> [!example]
> Accoding to the principle of least privilege, a teacher should be given access only to the students in his or her classes and only for the particular classes he or she takes.
>
> - If one teacher's account is compromised, only grades for that teacher's classes can be compromised

## Roles

![../60-Meta-Attachments/b0b59d61f57161685f3af5bfcc3b5a5b.png](data:image/png;base64,)

### Admin

- At the top of the tree diagram is one or more administrators who **have access and the ability to do bulk changes across the entire system**.
- This could be given to an **IT manager**, **principals**, or **vice-principals**.
- The strictest security measures should be in place for this level
  - (such as strong [[62-Encyclopedic/20220319080333-passwords|passwords]], tamper-resistant hardware tokens, and biometric authentication measures).
- If an attacker is able to gain access to the administrator account, he or she can **do the most damage** at this level.

### Report Generator

- At the next layer, there might be an account level that has read-only grade report access, which might be granted to other school administrators
- This level would have access to a process that generates reports of student grades across different classes and grade levels.
- If an attacker were to gain access to the report generator account, her or she could read all the reports but would not be able to change anything.

### Teacher of Specific Classes

- At the next layer, we have teachers who are given access to their specific classes.
- If an attacker were able to get into a teacher account, he or she would only be able to change the grades that the teacher has access to, without the ability to affect other teachersâ€™ classes.
